{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LuQmDhtdDcSbiuoNNn4SEw","type":"tool_result","content":"Todos have been modified successfully. Ensure that you continue to use the todo list to track your progress. Please proceed with the current tasks if applicable"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ead0a24a-8a66-467d-a3b3-f81605cf654f","uuid":"7a07469b-d596-4290-a745-968eb732c4dc","timestamp":"2026-03-31T21:49:09.670Z","tool_use_result":{"oldTodos":[{"content":"Analyze grpc-go metadata.go changes (PR #1157)","status":"in_progress","activeForm":"Analyzing grpc-go metadata.go changes"},{"content":"Find all etcd files importing grpc/metadata with old API","status":"pending","activeForm":"Finding affected etcd files"},{"content":"Analyze transitive metadata forwarding patterns","status":"pending","activeForm":"Analyzing metadata forwarding patterns"},{"content":"Write IMPACT_REPORT.md and answer.json","status":"pending","activeForm":"Writing impact report and JSON output"}],"newTodos":[{"content":"Analyze grpc-go metadata.go changes (PR #1157)","status":"completed","activeForm":"Analyzing grpc-go metadata.go changes"},{"content":"Find all etcd files importing grpc/metadata with old API","status":"completed","activeForm":"Finding affected etcd files"},{"content":"Analyze transitive metadata forwarding patterns","status":"completed","activeForm":"Analyzing metadata forwarding patterns"},{"content":"Write IMPACT_REPORT.md and answer.json","status":"in_progress","activeForm":"Writing impact report and JSON output"}],"verificationNudgeNeeded":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FagkLHB4YovgcZArkuze8W","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Tw8U3UEPYM9VQ1SG4Hg8cD","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/analysis/IMPACT_REPORT.md","content":"# Impact Analysis: gRPC-Go Metadata Context Separation (PR #1157)\n\n## 1. Breaking API Changes\n\nPR #1157 removed the two deprecated compatibility shims that had served as the single-unified metadata API. The old `metadata.FromContext` / `metadata.NewContext` pair was split into separate incoming/outgoing variants:\n\n| Old API (removed) | Replacement | Direction |\n|---|---|---|\n| `metadata.FromContext(ctx)` | `metadata.FromIncomingContext(ctx)` | Server-side: read metadata from a client RPC arriving at the server |\n| `metadata.FromContext(ctx)` | `metadata.FromOutgoingContext(ctx)` | Client-side: read metadata attached to an outgoing client RPC |\n| `metadata.NewContext(ctx, md)` | `metadata.NewOutgoingContext(ctx, md)` | Client-side: attach metadata to an outgoing client call |\n| _(new)_ | `metadata.NewIncomingContext(ctx, md)` | Server simulation: inject metadata as if it arrived from a client |\n| _(new)_ | `metadata.AppendToOutgoingContext(ctx, kv...)` | Efficiently append key-value pairs to outgoing metadata |\n\n### Key semantic distinction introduced by the split\n\nBefore the split, `FromContext` was literally an alias for `FromIncomingContext`. This meant:\n- A client that called `metadata.FromContext` on its own outgoing context would always get `(nil, false)` — it was silently reading the wrong slot.\n- A proxy that called `metadata.NewContext` to attach metadata would store it in the **outgoing** slot, which is correct for client-side use, but any downstream code that tried to read it back with `FromContext` (≡ `FromIncomingContext`) would see nothing.\n\nThe removal of the aliases forces callers to explicitly declare intent, eliminating the ambiguity.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Affected etcd Files — Breakage Classification\n\n**Verdict: etcd has been fully migrated. Zero uses of the removed API exist in the codebase.** All files use the correct split API. The table below documents every file that imports `google.golang.org/grpc/metadata` and what new API it uses, along with what would have happened if it had still been on the old API.\n\n| File | New API Used | If Still on Old API: Breakage Type |\n|---|---|---|\n| `client/v3/ctx.go` | `FromOutgoingContext`, `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** (`FromContext`/`NewContext` not found) |\n| `client/v3/watch.go` | `FromOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `client/v3/lease.go` | `FromOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `client/v3/ctx_test.go` | `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `client/v3/watch_test.go` | `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `server/auth/store.go` | `FromIncomingContext`, `NewIncomingContext` | **Compile error** + see note below |\n| `server/auth/store_test.go` | `NewIncomingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `server/proxy/grpcproxy/util.go` | `FromIncomingContext` | **Compile error** (proxy critical — see §3) |\n| `server/proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go` | Context propagation via `stream.Context()` | No direct call, unaffected |\n| `server/proxy/grpcproxy/lease.go` | Context propagation via `ctx` passthrough | No direct call, unaffected |\n| `server/proxy/grpcproxy/adapter/chan_stream.go` | `metadata.MD` type only | No function call, unaffected |\n| `server/etcdserver/api/v3rpc/interceptor.go` | `FromIncomingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `pkg/grpc_testing/recorder.go` | `FromIncomingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `tests/integration/v3_grpc_test.go` | `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `tests/integration/v3_lease_test.go` | `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `tests/integration/clientv3/watch_test.go` | `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n\n> **auth/store.go special note:** `WithRoot` uses `NewIncomingContext` to synthetically inject a root auth token into the context for internal server-initiated calls (e.g., lease revocations triggered by the etcdserver itself). If this had used the old `NewContext` (≡ `NewOutgoingContext`), the token would have been stored in the wrong slot — `AuthInfoFromCtx` reads from the **incoming** slot via `FromIncomingContext`, so it would have seen an empty token, silently denying auth. This is a **runtime behavior change** (silent auth failure), not a compile error.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Critical: Metadata Forwarding (Interceptors / Auth Proxy)\n\nThese files forward metadata from an **incoming** server-side RPC to an **outgoing** client-side RPC. They are the highest-risk category because a mismatch in context slots causes metadata to be silently dropped — no compile error, no panic, just missing data at runtime.\n\n### `server/proxy/grpcproxy/util.go` — Auth Token Forwarding Chain\n\nThis file implements the complete incoming→outgoing token forwarding pipeline:\n\n```\nIncoming RPC (server context, token in incoming metadata slot)\n    │\n    ▼  metadata.FromIncomingContext(ctx) → token string\n    │\n    ▼  withClientAuthToken: stored in context.Value (plain string, not metadata slot)\n    │\n    ▼  AuthUnaryClientInterceptor / AuthStreamClientInterceptor\n       reads token from getAuthTokenFromClient / ctx.Value\n       wraps in proxyTokenCredential (implements credentials.PerRPCCredentials)\n       appended as grpc.PerRPCCredentials call option\n    │\n    ▼\nOutgoing RPC to upstream etcd (token re-attached as fresh gRPC metadata)\n```\n\n**Why this design is safe:** The proxy intentionally does NOT use `metadata.NewOutgoingContext` to bulk-copy the incoming metadata map. Instead it extracts only the auth token and re-attaches it via `PerRPCCredentials`. This avoids the slot-confusion trap entirely.\n\n**What would break without migration:** If `getAuthTokenFromClient` still called `metadata.FromContext` (which equals `FromIncomingContext`) instead of `metadata.FromIncomingContext`, it would still work because the proxy *is* the server side — incoming metadata is the right slot. However, any client-side code that called `metadata.FromContext` to inspect an outgoing context (e.g., `client/v3/watch.go`'s `streamKeyFromCtx`, which reads outgoing MD) would silently get `(nil, false)`, causing stream deduplication logic to break at runtime with no error.\n\n### `server/etcdserver/api/v3rpc/interceptor.go` — Server Interceptors\n\nBoth `newUnaryInterceptor` and `newStreamInterceptor` call `metadata.FromIncomingContext` to inspect:\n- `MetadataClientAPIVersionKey` — client API version for metrics tagging\n- `MetadataRequireLeaderKey` — gate requests on leader availability\n\nThese are read-only inspections of incoming metadata. No forwarding occurs. Risk: compile error only if on old API.\n\n### `server/auth/store.go` — `WithRoot` Internal Token Injection\n\nUses `metadata.NewIncomingContext` to inject a root auth token for internal server calls. This is an explicit **incoming→incoming** simulation, not a forwarding pattern, but it is semantically critical:\n\n```go\n// CORRECT: NewIncomingContext so AuthInfoFromCtx (which calls FromIncomingContext) finds the token\nreturn metadata.NewIncomingContext(ctx, tokenMD)\n\n// WRONG (if NewContext / NewOutgoingContext were used):\n// AuthInfoFromCtx would call FromIncomingContext and get (nil, false) → silent auth failure\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Summary\n\n| Category | Count | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| Files with compile errors (old API) | 13 | **All migrated — no compile errors** |\n| Files with runtime behavior risk (wrong slot) | 1 (`auth/store.go` `WithRoot`) | **Migrated correctly** |\n| Critical metadata forwarding files | 1 (`proxy/grpcproxy/util.go`) | **Migrated; uses safe PerRPCCredentials pattern** |\n| Files using `metadata.MD` type only | 2 | Unaffected |\n\nThe etcd codebase is safe to upgrade grpc-go past the PR #1157 removal point. No uses of the deprecated `metadata.FromContext` or `metadata.NewContext` exist. The most architecturally sensitive file — `server/proxy/grpcproxy/util.go` — uses a forwarding pattern (extract token → `PerRPCCredentials`) that sidesteps the incoming/outgoing slot distinction, making it robust against this class of API change.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1278,"cache_read_input_tokens":27883,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1278},"output_tokens":18,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ead0a24a-8a66-467d-a3b3-f81605cf654f","uuid":"077aff7f-7153-4b51-a65c-f8a6a2442e32"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Tw8U3UEPYM9VQ1SG4Hg8cD","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /workspace/analysis/IMPACT_REPORT.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ead0a24a-8a66-467d-a3b3-f81605cf654f","uuid":"882bcdd7-5ec4-473d-88cc-0557b850ef9d","timestamp":"2026-03-31T21:49:49.898Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/workspace/analysis/IMPACT_REPORT.md","content":"# Impact Analysis: gRPC-Go Metadata Context Separation (PR #1157)\n\n## 1. Breaking API Changes\n\nPR #1157 removed the two deprecated compatibility shims that had served as the single-unified metadata API. The old `metadata.FromContext` / `metadata.NewContext` pair was split into separate incoming/outgoing variants:\n\n| Old API (removed) | Replacement | Direction |\n|---|---|---|\n| `metadata.FromContext(ctx)` | `metadata.FromIncomingContext(ctx)` | Server-side: read metadata from a client RPC arriving at the server |\n| `metadata.FromContext(ctx)` | `metadata.FromOutgoingContext(ctx)` | Client-side: read metadata attached to an outgoing client RPC |\n| `metadata.NewContext(ctx, md)` | `metadata.NewOutgoingContext(ctx, md)` | Client-side: attach metadata to an outgoing client call |\n| _(new)_ | `metadata.NewIncomingContext(ctx, md)` | Server simulation: inject metadata as if it arrived from a client |\n| _(new)_ | `metadata.AppendToOutgoingContext(ctx, kv...)` | Efficiently append key-value pairs to outgoing metadata |\n\n### Key semantic distinction introduced by the split\n\nBefore the split, `FromContext` was literally an alias for `FromIncomingContext`. This meant:\n- A client that called `metadata.FromContext` on its own outgoing context would always get `(nil, false)` — it was silently reading the wrong slot.\n- A proxy that called `metadata.NewContext` to attach metadata would store it in the **outgoing** slot, which is correct for client-side use, but any downstream code that tried to read it back with `FromContext` (≡ `FromIncomingContext`) would see nothing.\n\nThe removal of the aliases forces callers to explicitly declare intent, eliminating the ambiguity.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Affected etcd Files — Breakage Classification\n\n**Verdict: etcd has been fully migrated. Zero uses of the removed API exist in the codebase.** All files use the correct split API. The table below documents every file that imports `google.golang.org/grpc/metadata` and what new API it uses, along with what would have happened if it had still been on the old API.\n\n| File | New API Used | If Still on Old API: Breakage Type |\n|---|---|---|\n| `client/v3/ctx.go` | `FromOutgoingContext`, `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** (`FromContext`/`NewContext` not found) |\n| `client/v3/watch.go` | `FromOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `client/v3/lease.go` | `FromOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `client/v3/ctx_test.go` | `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `client/v3/watch_test.go` | `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `server/auth/store.go` | `FromIncomingContext`, `NewIncomingContext` | **Compile error** + see note below |\n| `server/auth/store_test.go` | `NewIncomingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `server/proxy/grpcproxy/util.go` | `FromIncomingContext` | **Compile error** (proxy critical — see §3) |\n| `server/proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go` | Context propagation via `stream.Context()` | No direct call, unaffected |\n| `server/proxy/grpcproxy/lease.go` | Context propagation via `ctx` passthrough | No direct call, unaffected |\n| `server/proxy/grpcproxy/adapter/chan_stream.go` | `metadata.MD` type only | No function call, unaffected |\n| `server/etcdserver/api/v3rpc/interceptor.go` | `FromIncomingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `pkg/grpc_testing/recorder.go` | `FromIncomingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `tests/integration/v3_grpc_test.go` | `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `tests/integration/v3_lease_test.go` | `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n| `tests/integration/clientv3/watch_test.go` | `NewOutgoingContext` | **Compile error** |\n\n> **auth/store.go special note:** `WithRoot` uses `NewIncomingContext` to synthetically inject a root auth token into the context for internal server-initiated calls (e.g., lease revocations triggered by the etcdserver itself). If this had used the old `NewContext` (≡ `NewOutgoingContext`), the token would have been stored in the wrong slot — `AuthInfoFromCtx` reads from the **incoming** slot via `FromIncomingContext`, so it would have seen an empty token, silently denying auth. This is a **runtime behavior change** (silent auth failure), not a compile error.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Critical: Metadata Forwarding (Interceptors / Auth Proxy)\n\nThese files forward metadata from an **incoming** server-side RPC to an **outgoing** client-side RPC. They are the highest-risk category because a mismatch in context slots causes metadata to be silently dropped — no compile error, no panic, just missing data at runtime.\n\n### `server/proxy/grpcproxy/util.go` — Auth Token Forwarding Chain\n\nThis file implements the complete incoming→outgoing token forwarding pipeline:\n\n```\nIncoming RPC (server context, token in incoming metadata slot)\n    │\n    ▼  metadata.FromIncomingContext(ctx) → token string\n    │\n    ▼  withClientAuthToken: stored in context.Value (plain string, not metadata slot)\n    │\n    ▼  AuthUnaryClientInterceptor / AuthStreamClientInterceptor\n       reads token from getAuthTokenFromClient / ctx.Value\n       wraps in proxyTokenCredential (implements credentials.PerRPCCredentials)\n       appended as grpc.PerRPCCredentials call option\n    │\n    ▼\nOutgoing RPC to upstream etcd (token re-attached as fresh gRPC metadata)\n```\n\n**Why this design is safe:** The proxy intentionally does NOT use `metadata.NewOutgoingContext` to bulk-copy the incoming metadata map. Instead it extracts only the auth token and re-attaches it via `PerRPCCredentials`. This avoids the slot-confusion trap entirely.\n\n**What would break without migration:** If `getAuthTokenFromClient` still called `metadata.FromContext` (which equals `FromIncomingContext`) instead of `metadata.FromIncomingContext`, it would still work because the proxy *is* the server side — incoming metadata is the right slot. However, any client-side code that called `metadata.FromContext` to inspect an outgoing context (e.g., `client/v3/watch.go`'s `streamKeyFromCtx`, which reads outgoing MD) would silently get `(nil, false)`, causing stream deduplication logic to break at runtime with no error.\n\n### `server/etcdserver/api/v3rpc/interceptor.go` — Server Interceptors\n\nBoth `newUnaryInterceptor` and `newStreamInterceptor` call `metadata.FromIncomingContext` to inspect:\n- `MetadataClientAPIVersionKey` — client API version for metrics tagging\n- `MetadataRequireLeaderKey` — gate requests on leader availability\n\nThese are read-only inspections of incoming metadata. No forwarding occurs. Risk: compile error only if on old API.\n\n### `server/auth/store.go` — `WithRoot` Internal Token Injection\n\nUses `metadata.NewIncomingContext` to inject a root auth token for internal server calls. This is an explicit **incoming→incoming** simulation, not a forwarding pattern, but it is semantically critical:\n\n```go\n// CORRECT: NewIncomingContext so AuthInfoFromCtx (which calls FromIncomingContext) finds the token\nreturn metadata.NewIncomingContext(ctx, tokenMD)\n\n// WRONG (if NewContext / NewOutgoingContext were used):\n// AuthInfoFromCtx would call FromIncomingContext and get (nil, false) → silent auth failure\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Summary\n\n| Category | Count | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| Files with compile errors (old API) | 13 | **All migrated — no compile errors** |\n| Files with runtime behavior risk (wrong slot) | 1 (`auth/store.go` `WithRoot`) | **Migrated correctly** |\n| Critical metadata forwarding files | 1 (`proxy/grpcproxy/util.go`) | **Migrated; uses safe PerRPCCredentials pattern** |\n| Files using `metadata.MD` type only | 2 | Unaffected |\n\nThe etcd codebase is safe to upgrade grpc-go past the PR #1157 removal point. No uses of the deprecated `metadata.FromContext` or `metadata.NewContext` exist. The most architecturally sensitive file — `server/proxy/grpcproxy/util.go` — uses a forwarding pattern (extract token → `PerRPCCredentials`) that sidesteps the incoming/outgoing slot distinction, making it robust against this class of API change.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
