ould be in the wrong slot and authentication would silently fail for all internal server-initiated operations.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"server/proxy/grpcproxy/watch.go\",\n      \"pattern\": \"context propagation — stream.Context() carries incoming metadata downstream\",\n      \"risk_if_unmigrated\": \"None directly; relies on util.go interceptors for token forwarding.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"file\": \"server/proxy/grpcproxy/lease.go\",\n      \"pattern\": \"context passthrough — incoming ctx passed directly to upstream client calls\",\n      \"risk_if_unmigrated\": \"None directly; relies on util.go interceptors for token forwarding.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"migration_status\": \"complete\",\n  \"old_api_usage_count\": 0,\n  \"summary\": \"The etcd codebase has been fully migrated to the split incoming/outgoing metadata API introduced in grpc-go PR #1157. No uses of the removed metadata.FromContext or metadata.NewContext exist. 13 files would have had compile errors on the old API; 1 file (server/auth/store.go WithRoot) would additionally have had a silent runtime auth failure. The most architecturally critical file is server/proxy/grpcproxy/util.go, which implements auth token forwarding from incoming server RPCs to outgoing proxied RPCs using a PerRPCCredentials pattern that is robust to the incoming/outgoing slot distinction.\",\n  \"severity\": {\n    \"level\": \"low\",\n    \"rationale\": \"Migration is already complete. No compile errors or runtime regressions will occur when upgrading grpc-go past the PR #1157 removal point. Historical severity of the API change was high — the removed functions introduced silent metadata loss bugs for any code that used FromContext to read outgoing contexts or NewContext/NewOutgoingContext followed by FromIncomingContext in the same context chain.\"\n  },\n  \"ownership\": \"grpc proxy and auth subsystems (server/proxy/grpcproxy/, server/auth/, server/etcdserver/api/v3rpc/, client/v3/)\"\n}\n"},"caller":{"type":"di